                    <marginalia_text> 
                        Ab hoc ferè Persei bello, et Æmilij Pauli de maximo rege triumpho, orditur Velleij Paterculi historia. In cuius primo 
                        libro, hi quatuor egregij viri; P. Æmilius, Q. Metellus, Scipio Æmilianus, L. Mummius. Secundus liber à bello Viriathi,
                        et Numantino, ad Tiberij vsq[ue] imperium; cui effusiùs blanditur: pra[e]clarus alioqui historicus, et diligenti animaduersione dignus.
                    </marginalia_text>
                <person name="Perseus"/>
                <person name="Paulus Aemilius Veronensis"/>
                <person name="Marcus Velleius Paterculus"/>
                <person name="Lucius Aemilius Paullus Macedonicus"/>
                <person name="Quintus Caecilius Metellus Macedonicus"/> 
                <person name="Scipio Aemilianus"/>
                <person name="Lucius Mummius Achaicus"/>
                <person name="Viriatus Lusitanus"/>
                <person name="Tiberius Gracchus"/>
                    <book title="Roman History"/>
                </position>
            </language>
            <translation>
                Approximately from this war of Perseus and Aemilius Paulus’ victory over the greatest king, commences the history of Velleius Paterculus. 
                In his first book appear these four extraordinary men: Paullus Aemilius , Quintus Metellus, Scipio Aemilianus and Lucius Mummius. 
                The second book [covers the period] from the war of Viriathus and the Numantine war to the rule of Tiberius, whom he flatters rather 
                immoderately; else a brilliant historian and worth careful attention.
            </translation>
        </marginalia>
        
